Name: Sam Disbrow
I solved the project by first identifying that execvp would be my main source of executing commands, and that I would need to create a fork as to not end the process. Next I looked at all of the other specifications that could happen, creating if statements to solve them. I had to think a little bit about how to print a report when backgrounded commands complete, however once I had the idea to save the pid's in a linked list, it became pretty simple. Piping was the hard part. I had originally been doing everything in main, but once I started working on piping, I decided it would be easier to switch it into its own separate function, so I pretty much just copy and pasted most of my code into a function, and made little changes where needed. Then I got to work on the piping and went through many possible ways to do it, such as just by making a pipe in an extra fork, which I found wouldn't work or with recursion, which turned out to be way more complicated than it needed to be. At this point I realized all I needed was to save a global variable for the output of the pipe, and then I just had issues with debugging, and once they were solved the program was done.
